04847nam a22005535i 9780822384694DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223846947 a10.1515/97808223846942doi  a(DE-B1597)553135  a(OCoLC)1226680346  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aR471.C8bP35 2003 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a610/.972862211 aPalmer, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Popular Medicine to Medical Populism :bDoctors, Healers, and Public Power in Costa Rica, 1800-1940 /cSteven Palmer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (346 p.) :b8 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Healers before Doctors -- t2 First Doctors, Licensed Empirics, and the New Politics of Practice -- t3 The Formation of a Biomedical Vanguard -- t4 Conventional Practice: New Science, Old Art, and Persistent Heterogeneity -- t5 Other Healers: Survival, Revival, and Public Endorsement -- t6 Midwives of the Republic -- t7 Hookworm Disease and the Popularization of Biomedical Practice -- t8 The Magician versus the Monopolists: The Popular Medical Eclecticism of Professor Carbell -- t9 Medical Populism: Dr. Calderón Guardia and the Foundations of Social Security -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Popular Medicine to Medical Populism presents the history of medical practice in Costa Rica from the late colonial era-when none of the fifty thousand inhabitants had access to a titled physician, pharmacist, or midwife-to the 1940s, when the figure of the qualified medical doctor was part of everyday life for many of Costa Rica's nearly one million citizens. It is the first book to chronicle the history of all healers, both professional and popular, in a Latin American country during the national period.Steven Palmer breaks with the view of popular and professional medicine as polar opposites-where popular medicine is seen as representative of the authentic local community and as synonymous with oral tradition and religious and magical beliefs and professional medicine as advancing neocolonial interests through the work of secular, trained academicians. Arguing that there was significant and formative overlap between these two forms of medicine, Palmer shows that the relationship between practitioners of each was marked by coexistence, complementarity, and dialogue as often as it was by rivalry. Palmer explains that while the professionalization of medical practice was intricately connected to the nation-building process, the Costa Rican state never consistently displayed an interest in suppressing the practice of popular medicine. In fact, it persistently found both tacit and explicit ways to allow untitled healers to practice. Using empirical and archival research to bring people (such as the famous healer or curandero Professor Carlos Carbell), events, and institutions (including the Rockefeller Foundation) to life, From Popular Medicine to Medical Populism demonstrates that it was through everyday acts of negotiation among agents of the state, medical professionals, and popular practitioners that the contours of Costa Rica's modern, heterogeneous health care system were established.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMedicinezCosta RicaxHistory. 0aSocial medicinezCosta RicaxHistory. 0aTraditional medicinezCosta RicaxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082238